# Arrays whose extent is not written in the specification.
#
# `T[]` means unbounded: each record carries its own length, in a
# `{count, pointer}` descriptor the loader builds from however many cells the
# row held. Nothing is fixed at compile time, so `.count` is a load and a
# quantifier is a loop.
#
# This file is run against two traces of different sizes *in one corpus*, on
# one compilation, and must hold for both. That used to be an error -- the
# extent was baked into the type, so traces that disagreed had to be rejected
# -- and it is the coupling the count exists to remove.

data    v : integer[];
data    g : integer[][];

# The extent is addressable, which is what makes a requirement able to talk
# about a size it did not write down.
v.count > 0;
g.count > 0;
g[0].count == 2;

# Quantifiers range over however many elements the trace turned out to have.
all x in v: x > 0;
some x in v: x == 1;
all row in g: all p in row: p > 0;
all _, i in v: i < v.count;

# The first element is always 1 in both traces; the last is v.count.
v[0] == 1;
